taxonomy.title: Period
taxonomy.description: This facet is an attempt at organizing and mining temporal information about an object. When was an object made or used? What decade, century, and/or millennium does that date [do those dates] correspond to? What events happened at that time? If numeric dates are not available, hooks are available [or will be soon] to latch date-, period-, era, event-, and reign- specific words or phrases and then assign beginning and end dates.
taxonomy.notes: In this first, experimental stab at organizing temporal data, inferences are always inductive and never deductive; i.e., general dates and periods are inferred from more specific dates, and never the other way around. A date of 1863 for an object will lead to an inference that the object dates to the American Civil War (1861 to 1865), but an object dated to the American Civil War will not be assigned dates of 1861, 1862, 1863, 1864, or 1865. This will need to be changed (perhaps once a 'specificity' or 'fuzzification' variable is introduced), but for the moment this sidesteps problems such as this: • Object X dates to 1895. • 1895 is inferred to be part of the second millennium. • A search for items from the first Crusade returns Object X because all more specific dates of the second millennium are inferred from the more general concept of '2nd Millennium.'
